<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-722-416  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 722 416.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Oct 1989 v14 n10 p279(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OCCCAM II. (programming language for INMOS transputer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pountain, Dick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A technical description of the Occam II programming language ispresented.andP;  Occam II is the latest version of Occam, a languagedeveloped for the INMOS parallel-processing transputer.andO;Conventional programming languages do not work with the vonNeumann parallel architecture used in the transputer because theyassume that the data is stored in main memory and lack I/Oinstructions.andP;  Occam builds the concepts of communication andconcurrent execution into its core and uses the 'process' as itsfundamental program element.andP;  Programs in Occam are built fromthree primitive processes: assignment, input, and output.andP;  Thelanguage lets users combine primitive processes through 'channel'functions and supports arrays of both processes and channels.andO;Occam's limitations include the fact that it is a static languageand that it is relatively low-level compared to most structuredlanguages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Parallel ProcessingProgramming LanguagesTechnologyConcurrent Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Parallel process diagramming elements. (chart)Two processes resulting in a third. (chart)Chaining processes. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>